definition.value: A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of m-hydroxyhippuric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of p-hydroxyhippuric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of undecanedioic acid.
A non-proteinogenic alpha-amino acid that is tryptophan in which the hydrogen at position 5 on the indole ring is replaced by a bromo group.
An organic anion obtained by removal of at least one proton from 1-methyluric acid.
An organic anion obtained by removal of at least one proton from 1,3-dimethyluric acid.
An organic anion obtained by removal of at least one proton from 1,7-dimethyluric acid.
An organic anion obtained by removal of at least one proton from 3,7-dimethyluric acid.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion which is obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of 2-hydroxyhexanoic acid.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any erythronic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 60 carbons and 12 double bonds.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-tafenoquine.
A tetrachlorobiphenyl that is biphenyl in which the hydrogens at position 3 and 4 on each phenyl group are replaced by chlorines.
A 3-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of acetoacetic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Any compound that can disrupt the functions of the endocrine (hormone) system
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-histidine with the amino group of L-phenylalanine.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-aminooctanoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 14 with 0 double bonds.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 16 with 1 double bond.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 18 with 0 double bonds.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 18 with 1 double bond.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 58 carbons and 12 double bonds.
A sterol 3-beta-D-glucoside resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of campesterol with beta-D-glucopyranose. Found in cloves, common wheat, and peaches.
A primary fatty amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (9Z)-hexadecenoic acid with ammonia.
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from selenic acid.
A 2,3,4-trihydroxybutanoate that is the conjugate base of threonic acid.
A purine nucleobase found in humans and other organisms.
The aldehyde formed from acetic acid by reduction of the carboxy group. It is the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke.
A methyl ketone that consists of propane bearing an oxo group at C2.
A choline that is the parent compound of the cholines class, consisting of ethanolamine having three methyl substituents attached to the amino function.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of pyruvic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A member of the class of benzoic acids that is salicylic acid in which the hydrogen that is attached to the phenolic hydroxy group has been replaced by an acetoxy group. A non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug with cyclooxygenase inhibitor activity.
A simple monocarboxylic acid containing two carbons.
A retinoic acid in which all four exocyclic double bonds have E- (trans-) geometry.
An enal that is prop-2-ene with an oxo group at position 1.
An oxygen hydride consisting of an oxygen atom that is covalently bonded to two hydrogen atoms
A sulfonium compound that is the S-adenosyl derivative of L-methionine. It is an intermediate in the metabolic pathway of methionine.
An adenosine 5'-phosphate in which the 5'-phosphate is a triphosphate group. It is involved in the transportation of chemical energy during metabolic pathways.
The simplest (and the only achiral) proteinogenic amino acid, with a hydrogen atom as its side chain.
